SALMONELLOSIS, SEROTYPE HEIDELBERG - USA (06): CHICKEN, CONTINUING ALERT
************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Continuing outbreak
[2] Legislation

******
[1] Continuing outbreak
Date: Wed 25 Jun 2014
Source: The Oregonian, Oregon Live [edited]
http://www.oregonlive.com/health/index.ssf/2014/06/foster_farms_outbreak_salmonel_1.html


The Foster Farms salmonella outbreak has continued to grow, with the number of infected people now surpassing 600. California health officials said that 27 new infections have been reported since 22 May 2014, with 468 patients confirmed so far. That puts the total tally nationwide at more than 600.

Infectious disease specialists at the CDC told The Oregonian that cases are continuing to trickle in. The CDC updates its case count periodically.

California health officials declined to provide specifics about whether those sickened had recently purchased Foster Farms chicken, but Dr Robert Tauxe, deputy director of the food-borne illness division at the CDC, said earlier this year [2014] that new cases were linked to fresh and not frozen chicken.

The outbreak has dragged on since March 2013, making it one of the longest in USA history, sickening people in 27 states, including Oregon and Washington, as well as Puerto Rico. It involves antibiotic-resistant strains of _Salmonella [enterica_ serotype] Heidelberg. Last month [May 2014] the Center for Science in the Public Interest sued the US Department of Agriculture over a petition to ban [sic] that strain and 3 others because of the threat to public health posed by superbugs. The USDA allows the sale of salmonella contaminated chicken, though it announced a plan last year [2013] to set a ceiling on the amount allowed on chicken parts, which is currently about 25 percent.

[Byline: Lynne Terry]

