[From the 2nd part of this posting:

"The USDA has set a 7.5 percent limit on salmonella on whole chickens but there is no ceiling on parts, which account for the majority of sales. It is currently working on a limit based on baseline studies in slaughterhouses which show a 25 percent contamination rate. For campylobacter, another pathogen associated with poultry, the USDA allows 10.4 percent on whole carcasses but again does not have a limit on parts. The bill names both salmonella and campylobacter as pathogens and says the ban would apply to bacteria that are resistant to 2 or more antibiotics considered to be critically important for human medicine by the World Health Organization. The WHO has sounded the alarm on the threat posed to human health by superbugs."

To this moderator, this continued scenario further underscores the need for consumers to understand that zero tolerance for certain enteric pathogens will likely never occur. Buyer beware, cooker beware, eater beware. Appropriate cooking and kitchen hygiene are the routes to safety. Note that the new legislation revolves around resistant bacteria. It is just as easy to die from a totally sensitive strain as from a resistant one. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2566071,106.]
